explanation:
OS_ObjectIdIterateActive - The call could be a macro/inline wrapper or call a helper that uses for-loops internally; the implementation must be inspected to ensure no ill-formed for statements are introduced by this iterator setup.

OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext - This function is used in the loop condition (while). Its implementation may contain for loops or have side-effects relevant to MISRA's for-loop rule (the rule counts behaviour of called functions inside loop constructs).

OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit - Callee of OS_ObjectIdIterateActive; its body may contain loop constructs (for) that need to be checked for MISRA compliance.

OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy - Called at end of iteration; it calls OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel and may contain loops itself; check for any for-loops or side-effects that could affect loop analysis.

OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel - Callee of OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy; include to inspect for loops or side effects inside destroy/transaction cleanup.

OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET - Likely a macro or inline accessor that maps token -> table entry; macro expansion could introduce a for loop or other control flow, so its definition must be examined.

OS_ObjectIndexFromToken - Appears in the static call graph as used by table-get; its implementation might use loops (for) or modify objects used in loop clauses; include to verify compliance.

OS_stream_table - Global object (table) accessed inside the loop body; need its declaration to understand any macros/indices that access it and whether accessors use for-loops or affect loop counters.

OS_stream_internal_record_t - The type of entries retrieved from OS_stream_table; include to confirm that accessing or copying fields (e.g., stream_name) does not invoke inline functions/macros that contain for-loops or modify loop counters.

OS_SocketDomain - The enum/constant set (e.g., OS_SocketDomain_INVALID) used in the loop body; include to ensure any macros or inline predicates using it do not expand into for-loops or modify loop control objects.

strcmp - Standard library call used in the loop body; include to confirm there are no project-specific wrappers/macros around strcmp that introduce additional control flow/for-loops or side-effects.

strncpy - Standard library call used in the loop body; include for same reason as strcmp (to check for wrappers/macros or inline variants that could contain for-loops or modify loop counters).
